areaDesc.3: Proximity to Packard. Sunlight Warren City Tank & Boiler Co. Grinnell Company, Youngstown Pressed Steel etc.
areaDesc.4: Very bad planning and poorly built homes
areaDesc.14: Warren City Tank & Boiler Company has offices south central section of this area. Loan commitments about 20% of appraisals here. Area has slight tendency to increase of colored population.

areaDesc.3: A good residential neighborhood, close to the business center. Community spirit evident. Double drive up Iddings. Known as Iddings Park.
areaDesc.14: Slavish Catholic Church just out of the area at the northwest which may have tendency to concentrate Slavish into C-2 and thence into B-7

areaDesc.2: Flat but high enough to be secure from floods
areaDesc.3: Air Reduction Sales Company. Chicago Car Roofing Co One Steel Mill also in area. School but no churches. Bus transportation.
areaDesc.4: B&O Railroad & Erie R.R. pass through area. Some streets unimproved

6.a: 2 apt. houses in area 4-5-6 rm singles

areaDesc.14: Section was built around old Western Reserve Steel Mill. This mill is gone now. This section probably worst in the city.

areaDesc.3: Factories near northwest section of this area. Restrictions - zoning residential. School, some churches. Stores adjacent on Niles Road & Youngstown Road.
areaDesc.14: Section is "killed" by influx of negroes from D-3 to attend Francis Willard School in C-8

areaDesc.2: Level - higher than business district and the Mahoning Avenue side of the river
areaDesc.3: Some restrictions. Bus transport is regular (30 minute intervals)
areaDesc.4: No schools, no stores, no churches. Necessary to cross railroad to go into area.
areaDesc.14: Southeastern part of area older - poorly planned except North Todd which is good. Garden Street along R.R. has houses 50 years old poor to fair condition. New street in - not shown on map about 30 houses on this street.

areaDesc.3: Well planned. Scenic features good. Overlooking Packard Park.
areaDesc.4: Churches, stores, schools, not conveniently near.
areaDesc.14: This area is on the so-called "west side" not easy of access and has been slow in developing for that reason.

areaDesc.2: Slopes slightly north from Railroad, otherwise level and high from east to west.
areaDesc.3: 5 Churches - 2 schools, nearby stores along W. Market, Parkman and Mason Streets. Transportation by bus along both north and south boundaries.
areaDesc.4: Concentration of negroes and foreign at western extremity on Nevada, Oregon and McNyler Streets. Commercial encroachment along W. Market and Summit Streets.
areaDesc.14: East of York Street nearly all American inhabitants

areaDesc.3: Adjacent to Packard Park. Roosevelt School in area.
areaDesc.4: Possible influx of lower grade population from C-6
areaDesc.14: about 6 very expensive homes along Mahoning at south end of area

areaDesc.3: Roosevelt School, 1 grade. Not far to factories. General Motors Plant, Ohio Lamp Factory, etc.
areaDesc.14: Good transportation, close to factories, school and churches also Fire Station in area.

areaDesc.3: Schools nearby in C-2 and C-7. Churches conveniently near in C-2. Walking distance of shopping center. Shade trees.
areaDesc.4: Proximity to R.R. and industry on north.
areaDesc.14: Sunlight new plant (G.M.) will be built just north of this area.

areaDesc.3: Close to city, fine shade trees, Central Jr. High School in area, churches, nearby shopping centers. Near the High School. Park adjacent to Perkins Circle.

6.a: 6-room singles; 10-15 rm old singles; Few converted duplex

areaDesc.14: Best section of area is at extreme west - Perkins Drive deserving Grade A but too small to be a separate area.

areaDesc.2: Level with slight rise eastward on Market Street. Slight depression of land along the railroad between Chestnut and Linden. Near shopping districts, and within walking distance of Republic Mill. Grade School in area. Churches in area.

6.a: 5-6 rm singles; Large old singles; Few apartments

areaDesc.14: Some large houses used as rooming houses along Porter & High Streets. Many owners moved out and rented their houses - holding them for a rise because of business encroaching. Central Jr. High School in area, also St. Mary's Catholic School, Elm Road School.

areaDesc.3: Schools in area. Close to High School in B4 area. Adjacent to factories (for those who work in factories)
areaDesc.14: Foreigners likely to invade this area. Home Saving & Loan Companies of Youngstown, also Trumbull had about 50 foreclosures in this area which were offered for sale in October 1936. All closed out now. Prices Average 3500, the amount of the mortgage.

areaDesc.3: High school in area. Grade school across street from the area in C-7 (Elm Road School)
areaDesc.4: Fair grounds in center of area between Atlantic and Woodland Avenue.
areaDesc.14: In 1929 this section was not so well developed as it is now. Also opening of Genesee Blvd. from E. Market to Elm Road and of Woodland Avenue to the Country Club has improved value in the area. The expensive houses in this area are generally along Fairmont & Bonnie Brae. Genessee.

areaDesc.2: Level - few trees in eastern end but beautiful trees in western section.
areaDesc.3: Attractive planning - adjacent Country Club - best school in city. Transportation (every 30 minutes) by bus.
areaDesc.4: No stores convenient, no churches nearby.
areaDesc.14: Paving assessments were high because of unnecessary expense of layout. In some cases the amount of special assessments exceed the price of the lot.

areaDesc.3: School nearby in A-1 area. Transportation through area. Shade trees plentiful.
areaDesc.14: This is the very best blue section

areaDesc.3: Grade school in area - churches - transportation through the area - bus line. Zoning restrictions.
areaDesc.14: Lots in this area are of good size. East Junior High School and Warren City Hospital in this area.

areaDesc.2: Flat - lowest built up section of city.
areaDesc.3: Close to mill. Business center available. Schools near, within walking distance of shopping center.
areaDesc.4: Concentration of disorderly houses along Fulton Street. Heavy paving assessment on Fulton Street. So. Park Ave Walnut street. Low grade population.
areaDesc.14: Rent decline due to improvidence of occupants. All work in Republic Steel, about 3 blocks away from the area.

areaDesc.3: Near Republic Steel Mill. Neighborhood stores.
areaDesc.4: Old property - Overflow at times of high water no schools.
areaDesc.14: Not quite as good as D-1, 20% lower rentals, 50% lower sales values. City dump adjacent to this property on west. Dump between Hayden and Steele St.s

areaDesc.2: Generally level with very slight slope toward river.
areaDesc.3: West side Jr. High School Palmyra & Austin, 3 churches. Neighborhood stores along Market, Highland Avenues. Quinby Park.
areaDesc.4: Southeastern portion of the area characterized by foreign and negro.

5.a: Factory workers, merchants and business men

6.c: West of Austin 12 yrs.; No. Central Sec 25 yrs.; S.E. Section 25 yrs.

areaDesc.13: Static except in west extremity where possibly up.
areaDesc.14: About 200 bungalows west of Austin. Todd Avenue out of city Limits (south) good prospects for favorable development.
